  abstract={As the core technology of autonomous driving, 3D object detection has attracted a great interest of lots of researchers. Many 3D object detection methods achieved promising performance. However, current 3D object detection method relies heavily on 3D annotation. The quantity and quality of annotation directly determine the performance of current 3D object detector, but 3D annotation is very expensive and require lots of human labor. Based upon the predicament described above, we proposed ST-PointRCNN: a semi-supervised 3D object detection method in autonomous driving, and achieves good results. Specifically, we apply student-teacher framework to train and improve the accuracy of the student model. We filter the predictions of teacher model and only keep high confidence predictions as pseudo labels. To expand the unlabeled data set and make the pseudo labels relatively more accurate than the predictions of student model, we design consistency losses for two-stage 3D object detection method to improve the robustness of the detector to data noise. Finally, we also conduct extensive experiments on KITTI dataset. The results show that comparing to the supervised method our method improve the average of car, pedestrian, and cyclist for easy difficulty by 8.8%, 9.4% and 7.1 % respectively when using 5% of label data.},
