  number={},
  pages={1-8},
  abstract={A dynamic adversarial adaptive bearing fault diagnosis method driven by a combination of simulation and data is proposed to solve the problem of low diagnostic accuracy of rolling bearings due to the scarcity of fault data samples and complex service conditions in real industrial scenarios. Firstly, a four-degree-of-freedom dynamics simulation model was proposed for the rapid generation of bearing fault characteristics with a well-defined time-frequency domain. Subsequently, the commonalities and differences between the measured data distribution and the dynamics simulation signal were explored. Finally, a dynamic adversarial adaptive network that can extract invariant features in the hidden domain and automatically align the distribution of data in the source domain of the simulation and the data to be diagnosed in the target domain is developed. A rolling bearing fault diagnosis simulation experiment was designed, which used the dynamic model to generate the simulated signal with label information and the measured signal without label information to train the neural network. The classification and recognition of unlabeled samples are completed. The results show that the simulated signals contain information on the characteristics of bearing faults, which can characterise real bearing data. Moreover, the proposed dynamic adversarial adaptive network can achieve more accurate fault diagnosis of bearings.},
